 | 

Just wanted to share something crucial that solved this issue for me. If you're using a cloud build system like EAS (Expo Application Services), the SHA-1 fingerprint you see locally might NOT be the one actually used in your built app.

I tried everything suggested (checking local debug.keystore, running ./gradlew signingReport, etc.) but kept getting the DEVELOPER_ERROR. The breakthrough came when I realized that EAS uses its own signing process, so I needed to:

- Download the actual built APK from EAS

- Extract its SHA-1 using:

`keytool -printcert -jarfile your-app.apk
`

- Use THAT SHA-1 in Google Cloud Console

The SHA-1 from the built APK was completely different from what I saw locally! After updating Google Cloud Console with this SHA-1, Google Sign-In started working immediately.

If you're using any cloud build service (EAS, Flutter, etc.), make sure to check the SHA-1 from your actual built APK, not just your local signing reports.

